1. Differnce between Faemon Set and StatefulSet in Kubernetes?
A: 
   DaemonSet - "One Pod Per Node", A DaemonSet ensure that exactly one pod runs on every node or selected node in the cluster.
               If a Node exists --> A Pod is automaticlly deployed on it. "DaemonSet is used when we need one pod per node for system-level or node-level operations"
   Characteristics: Runs 1 pod per node, Automatically adds/removes pods when nodes join/leave, Used for background/system services, Pods are stateless
   Common Use Cases: Logging agents, Monitoring agents, Security tools
   Real Examples: Fluentd → Collect logs from each node
                  Prometheus Node Exporter → Collect node metrics
                  Datadog Agent → Node monitoring

   StatefulSet: A StatefulSet is used to manage stgzateful applications where each pod has: Stable identity, Persisten storage, ordered deployment.
                “StatefulSet is used when applications need stable identity, persistent storage, and ordered scaling.”
   Characteristics: Pods have unique names (e.g., db-0, db-1), Each pod gets its own persistent volume, Ordered start/stop, Used for stateful apps
   Common Use Cases: Databases, Distributed systems, Clustered apps
   Real Examples: MySQL, MongoDB, Apache Kafka

   When to use DaemonSet? “If I want to run a logging agent like Fluentd on every node to collect logs, I would use a DaemonSet.”
   When to use StatefulSet? “If I am deploying a database like MySQL where each instance needs its own storage and identity, I would use a StatefulSet.”
   Simple Real-World Analogy:
               DaemonSet = Security guard in every building 
               StatefulSet = Hotel rooms with fixed room numbers 

“DaemonSet ensures one pod runs on every node, mainly for node-level services like logging and monitoring. StatefulSet is used for stateful applications like databases where each pod has a stable identity, persistent storage, and ordered deployment.”

