2. How to connect a specific container from a web browser (network) in k8s? How traffic flows from browser → cluster → pod?

A: "We cannot directly access a container from a browser. We expose it using a Kubernetes Service like NodePort or Loadbalancer. In production, we typically use Ingress with a controller like NGINX to route traffic using domain names and enable SSL.
  The Service routes external traffic to the correct pod/container using labels and selectors."

  NodePort: Opens a port on every node --> You access using: http://<NodeIP>:<NodePort> ----->>> “NodePort is mainly used for testing, not recommended for production.”
  LoadBalancer: Cloud provider gives external IP --> Works in: GCP, AWS, Azure ------>>> “Used in production because it provides external IP automatically.”
  Ingress:  Routes traffic using domain names --> Works at HTTP/HTTPS layer ----->>> “Ingress is preferred in production because it provides routing, SSL, and domain-based access.”

  Traffic Flow: Browser → Ingress → Service → Pod → Container OR Browser → NodeIP:NodePort → Service → Pod → Container

DevOps Scenario: “In my project, I deployed a frontend app using Kubernetes. Initially, I used NodePort for testing. Later, in production, I exposed the application using Ingress with an NGINX Ingress Controller and configured a domain like myapp.com with SSL. 
This allowed users to access the container via browser securely.”

