3. What are kubernetes services and why we use this?
A:
   Definition: "A k8s service is an abstraction that expose a set of pods as a network service, providing a stable IP and DNS name to access them."
Why do we need a Service?
   Pods in Kubernetes are dynamic: Pod IPs change when restarted -> Pods can be scaled up/down -> Pods can dies ------>>> So directly accessing Pods is unreliable.
   Problem: Pod-1 → 10.1.1.5 (dies) -> Pod-2 → 10.1.1.9 (new IP)
   Solution:
        Service gives: Stable IP (ClusterIP), DNS name, Load balancing
  Simple Explanation: “Service acts like a load balancer and stable endpoint in front of pods.”  
  Flow: Client → Service → Pod (via labels & selectors) -> Service uses labels -> Routes traffic to matching pods.

ClusterIP: Default and use Internal communication (Inside Cluster) Ex: https://nginx-service
NodePost: Expose app externally Ex: http://NodeIP:30007
LoadBalancer: Use in Production and works on GCP, AWS, Azure...
ExternalName: Map service to external DNS.

Real DevOps: “In my project, we deployed a microservices application where the frontend communicates with backend APIs using Kubernetes Services. We used ClusterIP for internal communication and Ingress for external traffic routing. 
This ensured stable communication even when pods were scaled or restarted.”

